00:23.240 --> 00:26.312
Hey, Mr. White. It's me. Um,

00:26.480 --> 00:30.190
I know you're probably
real busy with retirement

00:30.360 --> 00:33.080
but I got some news I think
you should maybe know about.

00:33.280 --> 00:35.476
Me and Declan had some
differences of opinion

00:35.680 --> 00:37.273
and it got a little...

00:38.080 --> 00:40.879
messy. Um...

00:41.400 --> 00:43.119
It's all straightened out now

00:43.280 --> 00:46.398
but just a heads-up, there's been
a kind of change in management.

00:46.560 --> 00:48.791
Anyway, just thought
you should know.

00:48.960 --> 00:51.475
Feel free to give me a call
if you want the details

00:51.640 --> 00:53.791
but, you know, it's cool,
so whatever.

00:54.240 --> 00:56.630
Okay, then. Thanks. Bye.

00:57.280 --> 00:59.795
<i>Right, so there I am,
I'm on top of the train,</i>

00:59.960 --> 01:02.350
pumping the water in,
he's watching to make sure we put in

01:02.520 --> 01:04.830
exactly what he'd calculated.

01:05.040 --> 01:06.595
We gotta be real precise because...

01:06.795 --> 01:08.351
water and methylene weigh different

01:08.560 --> 01:10.040
and he figured it all out

01:10.200 --> 01:12.590
to, like, milliliter.
I'm up there with my hose,

01:12.800 --> 01:15.474
we're going as fast as we can.
We only got a few minutes.

01:15.640 --> 01:18.792
At the crossing, we got this guy
who's smooth-talking the engineer.

01:18.960 --> 01:20.519
And it's all just going great

01:20.720 --> 01:24.350
until this other dude shows up
in this monster truck

01:24.560 --> 01:27.075
so we're pretty much screwed,
because he can just push

01:27.240 --> 01:30.711
the entire dump truck off the tracks,
which, you know, is what he does.

01:30.880 --> 01:32.200
Wait. What's your guy doing?

01:32.400 --> 01:34.915
You can't stop him?
Yeah, but what's he gonna say?

01:35.080 --> 01:39.677
"Thanks anyway, sir, but my friends
are still stealing cargo back there."

01:39.840 --> 01:42.480
So I'm looking all around,
because I know we're not done,

01:42.640 --> 01:44.597
but the gallons
are slowly ticking away.

01:44.760 --> 01:46.592
And finally Mr. White
tells me to cut it.

01:46.760 --> 01:48.084
So I fling the hose,

01:48.184 --> 01:49.958
I'm grabbing the cap,
I'm screwing in the bolts.

01:50.120 --> 01:52.112
Just, like, busting ass, you know?

01:52.280 --> 01:57.594
And then I feel the train
start moving and I'm...

01:57.800 --> 01:59.519
You're...
I'm on top.

01:59.720 --> 02:02.155
Did you piss your pants?
Yeah, right?

02:02.320 --> 02:06.633
So the thing starts speeding up,
so I jump off the moving train.

02:06.800 --> 02:08.074
Like, total stuntman stuff.

02:08.240 --> 02:10.596
It's like <i>Hooper.</i>
You ever see <i>Hooper?</i>

02:10.759 --> 02:12.558
Oh, hey, man, Burt Reynolds.
Good movie.

02:12.720 --> 02:14.552
He jumped out of a helicopter,
not a train.

02:14.720 --> 02:16.154
Whatever, man.
It's a good movie.

02:16.360 --> 02:19.990
This guy Jesse, he's underneath,
and the train just drives right over him.

02:20.200 --> 02:22.510
And luckily
he's this skinny little guy.

02:22.880 --> 02:25.634
Damn.
That's a tight operation.

02:25.800 --> 02:28.395
It was perfect.

02:29.080 --> 02:32.710
No one even knew they got robbed,
just like we planned.

02:32.920 --> 02:36.630
Mr. White told me it was, like,
the biggest train heist ever,

02:36.840 --> 02:38.638
like, potential money-wise.

02:38.840 --> 02:40.991
So that's how that happened.
Ha, ha.

02:49.640 --> 02:51.597
Can I get you anything else?

02:52.160 --> 02:53.879
Nope. Thanks, darling.

02:54.040 --> 02:56.077
I'm ready for the check.

03:10.600 --> 03:13.240
You feeling good
about cooking?

03:14.040 --> 03:15.872
Yeah.

03:17.040 --> 03:19.874
You'll be able to
run your own lab?

03:20.040 --> 03:22.839
Do it up right?
Yeah. For sure. I got this.

03:26.360 --> 03:27.953
All right.

03:28.600 --> 03:32.480
Let's make some money, then.
I gotta hit the head.

03:38.160 --> 03:39.992
Ever been on a plane
and find yourself

03:40.160 --> 03:42.356
looking down at the armrest
next to you,

03:42.520 --> 03:46.560
looking at the little plug
where the ashtray used to go?

03:46.720 --> 03:48.008
I look at that and I say,

03:48.208 --> 03:50.270
"What the hell happened to this country?"

03:50.440 --> 03:51.794
Nanny state.

03:52.000 --> 03:53.832
I see a kid with
a bicycle helmet on,

03:54.040 --> 03:57.556
I wanna smack the shit out of him,
like, for his own good.

04:31.440 --> 04:33.477
<i># Gonna romp, stomp
Swing with you, baby #</i>

04:33.640 --> 04:35.757
<i># Gonna romp, stomp
Sway with you, baby #</i>

04:35.960 --> 04:37.758
<i># Gonna romp, stomp
Rock with you, baby #</i>

04:37.960 --> 04:39.872
<i># Gonna romp, stomp
Roll with you, baby #</i>

04:40.040 --> 04:45.354
<i># Gonna romp, stomp
Romp and stomp tonight ##</i>

05:41.040 --> 05:42.474
Mr. Pinkman.

05:43.120 --> 05:45.032
How are you today?

05:46.240 --> 05:47.276
Not so good, huh?

05:48.480 --> 05:53.191
Of course, I might be able
to help you out.

05:54.320 --> 05:57.597
I wanna talk to you about
your partner, Heisenberg.

05:58.440 --> 06:01.558
See, I know
he's my brother-in-law, Walt.

06:03.360 --> 06:06.831
Oh, yeah. That's the look.

06:09.840 --> 06:14.437
Lucky for you,
I'm more interested in him.

06:14.840 --> 06:16.832
So I got an offer.

06:17.800 --> 06:19.996
If you help me out here,

06:21.120 --> 06:26.559
tell me all about you and him
and your little meth business,

06:27.360 --> 06:30.558
maybe I talk to my friends
at the A.P.D.

06:30.760 --> 06:32.752
and make all this go away.

06:34.360 --> 06:37.080
I know he's the mastermind here.

06:37.640 --> 06:39.313
Plus...

06:40.400 --> 06:43.871
I'm thinking,
based on your recent activities,

06:44.040 --> 06:48.432
that maybe there's
a little trouble in paradise?

06:49.360 --> 06:53.354
Maybe you guys aren't
getting along so good?

06:55.200 --> 06:56.919
I'm right, aren't I?

06:57.760 --> 06:59.638
Eat me.

07:01.640 --> 07:04.155
Sure that's how
you want to play this?

07:05.240 --> 07:09.120
Why don't you try
and beat it out of me?

07:10.000 --> 07:12.595
That's your thing, right?

07:22.200 --> 07:24.590
He really did a number on you,
didn't he?

07:31.800 --> 07:33.996
I don't know,

07:35.280 --> 07:39.957
but happy people
usually don't go around

07:41.200 --> 07:43.715
throwing millions of dollars away.

07:45.120 --> 07:47.316
I don't think

07:47.520 --> 07:51.230
Walt's gonna be patting you
on the back for that.

07:52.800 --> 07:54.917
But maybe that's the point.

07:57.320 --> 07:59.152
But, you see, I get that.

07:59.840 --> 08:01.877
My own brother-in-law,

08:02.080 --> 08:05.152
lying to me for over a year.

08:06.720 --> 08:08.279
Using me.

08:09.560 --> 08:11.995
Maybe you understand
that feeling.

08:16.040 --> 08:18.350
Help me out here, Jesse...

08:20.000 --> 08:21.798
and we can put him away.

08:23.560 --> 08:25.597
I know you want that.

08:27.880 --> 08:29.872
I think you wanna talk.

08:35.400 --> 08:37.153
Not to you.

08:38.480 --> 08:41.154
Agent Schrader,
beat any good suspects lately?

08:41.320 --> 08:44.073
Tall and taller, ask him
about his history with my client.

08:44.240 --> 08:47.074
He knocked the poor kid unconscious
last time they were alone.

08:47.240 --> 08:50.312
So, what'll it be, a civil rights
lawsuit the size of Montana?

08:50.480 --> 08:52.039
Because I'll oblige you.

08:52.840 --> 08:55.230
Oh. So long, Rocky.
Keep your left up.

08:55.400 --> 08:57.357
Detectives,
I'm inviting you to leave.

08:58.160 --> 08:59.753
I'm gonna try to remain calm,

08:59.920 --> 09:03.470
but will you do me a favor
and tell me what is up with you?

09:03.640 --> 09:06.792
My guys are busting their asses

09:06.960 --> 09:10.397
trying to hide Walt's money
from the feds

09:10.560 --> 09:12.711
and you're tossing yours
out a window?

09:12.880 --> 09:17.352
And I have to hear about your little act
of philanthropy on the news?

09:17.520 --> 09:19.318
Did you hit your head
or something?

09:19.480 --> 09:22.200
Why didn't you call me
the second you got arrested?

09:22.360 --> 09:24.079
What did you say
to Schrader?

09:24.240 --> 09:26.152
Nothing. Jesus. Just chill out.

09:26.320 --> 09:28.880
Chill out? No.
No, I don't chill out right now

09:29.040 --> 09:31.475
because things
have gone nuclear.

09:32.120 --> 09:36.194
I imagine Schrader shared
with you his recent discovery.

09:37.040 --> 09:40.431
Okay, well, then you get
my complete lack of chill.

09:42.640 --> 09:45.360
Just use the money
that I gave you.

09:45.560 --> 09:47.313
No, Saul. Saul, I...

09:47.520 --> 09:48.510
Stop... Saul.

09:48.680 --> 09:52.037
Stop talking. I don't care.

09:52.200 --> 09:55.716
Just... Just make it happen.
Work your magic.

09:55.880 --> 09:57.997
And call me when he's out.

09:58.200 --> 09:59.873
Hey, Dad, I'm home.

10:00.040 --> 10:02.600
Oh, okay. I'll be right out.

10:02.760 --> 10:06.754
Hey, you going to work today?
You were out late last night.

10:07.480 --> 10:10.075
Huh? I... Well, I, uh...

10:10.240 --> 10:13.233
Yeah, I guess I just lost track of time.

10:40.720 --> 10:42.473
Dad.
Huh?

10:42.640 --> 10:45.474
I'm gonna head out, okay?

10:46.280 --> 10:49.717
Where you going?
Uh, Aunt Marie just called.

10:49.880 --> 10:54.079
She wants me to help her
with some computer thing

10:54.240 --> 10:56.277
and asked me to stay for dinner.

10:56.440 --> 10:57.999
That cool?

10:59.640 --> 11:02.394
Uh... I guess that...

11:02.560 --> 11:04.756
Cool. All right, see you later.

11:05.920 --> 11:08.310
Wait, uh, son?

11:08.520 --> 11:10.352
Junior. Hang on a second.
Yeah?

11:10.560 --> 11:13.473
Oh, good. Come on back inside.
What happened?

11:13.640 --> 11:15.996
Oh, this? Nothing.
No, I'm fine. It's fine.

11:16.160 --> 11:18.072
Really. I do wanna talk to you, though.

11:18.280 --> 11:20.078
Okay. Are you okay?

11:20.280 --> 11:22.351
Yeah. Here.
Sit down a second.

11:27.120 --> 11:29.794
I just don't wanna keep things
from you, okay?

11:30.000 --> 11:32.117
I mean, you deserve to know
what's happening.

11:35.240 --> 11:37.311
Yesterday, I passed out.

11:37.480 --> 11:39.551
Briefly. Very, very briefly.

11:39.760 --> 11:40.796
And I did this.

11:43.120 --> 11:45.715
Why did you pass out?

11:45.880 --> 11:50.159
Well, my latest scans

11:50.320 --> 11:55.395
show a little shadow on my lung.

11:56.120 --> 12:00.034
But my doctor put me right on
a new round of chemo,

12:00.240 --> 12:02.311
which is why
I've been so tired lately.

12:02.480 --> 12:04.233
But I was pushing myself too hard.

12:04.400 --> 12:07.393
I know it.
I just don't want you to worry.

12:07.560 --> 12:08.596
I learned my lesson.

12:09.280 --> 12:12.239
Well, um, what's the...?

12:13.760 --> 12:15.160
What now?

12:15.880 --> 12:20.796
What now is that we go on,
like always. Right?

12:23.320 --> 12:25.880
Hey, don't worry about this,
okay?

12:26.040 --> 12:29.033
I know that's hard,
but I beat this once.

12:29.200 --> 12:32.113
There's no reason to think
I won't again.

12:33.320 --> 12:35.551
And my doctor says
I'm doing great.

12:35.720 --> 12:38.474
I'm responding really well
to the treatment.

12:38.640 --> 12:40.359
And I'm...

12:40.520 --> 12:45.037
I'm feeling very...
Very good about this, all right?

12:45.240 --> 12:47.800
And what would really
help me out

12:48.320 --> 12:51.074
is if we all stayed positive.

12:51.920 --> 12:53.718
Can we do that?

12:55.200 --> 12:56.998
Yeah?

12:57.480 --> 12:58.550
Hm?

12:58.720 --> 13:00.632
Okay.

13:02.200 --> 13:04.351
So why don't you go
and help your Aunt Marie

13:04.560 --> 13:09.510
and we'll talk about this later?
No. No. No way.

13:09.720 --> 13:13.396
I'm staying. I'm not leaving.

13:22.800 --> 13:24.917
Flynn is not with you, is he?
No.

13:25.080 --> 13:26.912
No. Why would he be?

13:29.120 --> 13:30.759
How'd it go?

13:31.720 --> 13:33.791
That bad, huh?

13:35.400 --> 13:37.756
How bad are we talking, Hank?

13:40.440 --> 13:42.238
I didn't tell them.

13:42.400 --> 13:43.959
Why not?

13:45.920 --> 13:49.436
It's just not time yet.
No, it's past time.

13:49.640 --> 13:52.109
Way past time.
We talked about this.

13:52.280 --> 13:54.636
You've got to tell them now.
It's gonna be worse

13:54.800 --> 13:57.713
if they find out that
you've kept this from them.

13:57.880 --> 14:01.112
Look, it's just I've got some things
I gotta chase down.

14:01.280 --> 14:03.078
What? What things?

14:03.800 --> 14:04.995
Leads, you know.

14:05.160 --> 14:06.992
What leads? What? Something new?

14:07.200 --> 14:09.920
I'm not keeping anything from anybody,
Marie, okay? Jesus.

14:10.080 --> 14:12.231
Don't tell me how to do my job.

14:17.080 --> 14:19.151
Walt.

14:20.280 --> 14:22.715
Are you sure about this?

14:24.480 --> 14:26.597
It's the only way.

14:31.160 --> 14:32.435
Okay.

14:38.680 --> 14:40.637
I'm ready.

14:43.960 --> 14:46.714
My name is Walter Hartwell White.

14:46.880 --> 14:49.315
I live at 308 Negra Arroyo Lane,

14:49.480 --> 14:53.235
Albuquerque, New Mexico, 87104.

14:54.720 --> 14:56.791
This is my confession.

15:17.720 --> 15:19.552
They're here.

15:44.000 --> 15:46.276
Thank you for coming.

15:52.480 --> 15:55.837
Okay, I'll start.

15:56.000 --> 15:58.674
Skyler and I...
Welcome to GarduÃ±o's.

15:58.840 --> 16:01.036
My name is Trent.
I'll be taking care of you.

16:01.100 --> 16:03.411
Can I start anybody off with some beverages?

16:03.611 --> 16:04.113
Margarita?

16:04.280 --> 16:06.670
How about some of
our tableside guacamole?

16:06.840 --> 16:10.754
I think we're fine.
We need some time with the menu.

16:10.920 --> 16:13.310
No worries.
Be right back with some water.

16:17.600 --> 16:19.432
So you here to confess?

16:26.440 --> 16:28.909
There's nothing to confess.

16:29.800 --> 16:32.156
We're here to talk about Walter, Jr.

16:32.320 --> 16:34.994
Flynn and Holly should be
living with us. End of story.

16:35.160 --> 16:37.914
And while
we respect your opinion,

16:38.800 --> 16:41.269
we think that your concern
is misplaced.

16:41.840 --> 16:46.471
Skyler and I feel,
due to Marie's attempt

16:46.640 --> 16:48.279
to lure him to your house...

16:48.480 --> 16:51.678
I wasn't trying to lure him.

16:51.840 --> 16:54.958
Regardless
of what you might call it,

16:55.120 --> 16:58.909
Skyler and I
would like to ask you

16:59.120 --> 17:03.353
to please leave
our children out of this.

17:03.520 --> 17:07.434
Junior has been through
a lot already this year.

17:08.359 --> 17:09.714
You are just...

17:09.920 --> 17:12.037
This investigation, Hank,

17:12.200 --> 17:14.874
do you realize
what this will do to him?

17:15.040 --> 17:16.234
Hearing these things?

17:16.400 --> 17:19.598
He's gonna hear it when I kick in
your front door and arrest you.

17:26.000 --> 17:30.472
If that day ever comes,
so be it.

17:30.640 --> 17:34.031
You have no evidence
to support your claims.

17:34.240 --> 17:37.551
Why tear this family apart?

17:39.600 --> 17:42.672
So how about that guacamole?

17:44.720 --> 17:47.918
We make it right here
at the table.

17:52.640 --> 17:55.280
I'll just give you guys
a few more minutes.

17:58.600 --> 18:01.832
How can you sit there
and listen to this?

18:02.000 --> 18:04.674
All we want is for those kids
to be safe.

18:04.840 --> 18:07.150
You're putting them in danger,
keeping them under the same roof...

18:07.320 --> 18:09.152
They are safe, Marie.

18:09.320 --> 18:13.439
You yourself sent them out of the house.
And I brought them back.

18:13.600 --> 18:17.230
Look, whatever you think he did,

18:17.400 --> 18:19.960
this is not an ongoing situation.

18:20.160 --> 18:21.310
Skyler.
No.

18:22.000 --> 18:26.392
They need to understand.
It's in the past.

18:26.560 --> 18:29.837
It's over.
There is nothing to go after here.

18:30.040 --> 18:31.440
There's nothing to accomplish.

18:31.600 --> 18:33.239
How can we believe
anything you say?

18:33.400 --> 18:36.154
There's no telling
where the lies begin and end.

18:36.320 --> 18:38.710
That affair of yours,
did that even happen?

18:38.880 --> 18:42.920
Please. Look, Junior just found out
that my cancer is back.

18:43.440 --> 18:47.070
He's already facing the idea
of living without his father.

18:47.240 --> 18:50.631
To put this on top of that?

18:52.600 --> 18:53.920
It's just not right.

18:54.080 --> 18:56.800
I swear to God,
you start throwing the word "right" at me...

18:56.960 --> 18:59.270
What I mean...
Was it right to run a drug empire?

18:59.440 --> 19:01.318
There is no drug empire.

19:01.480 --> 19:03.119
Lying to your son,
to all of us, is that right?

19:03.280 --> 19:05.397
What do I have to do
to make you believe me?

19:05.560 --> 19:07.517
Why don't you kill yourself,
Walt?

19:09.120 --> 19:11.157
- What?
- Just kill yourself.

19:11.320 --> 19:14.233
This whole thing dies with you.
That's what you're saying here?

19:14.400 --> 19:19.236
Is that Hank should just let it go
and wait for you to die.

19:20.360 --> 19:22.795
Well, maybe you should just
go ahead and die, then.

19:23.960 --> 19:29.194
That is not a solution.
No, it's not a solution.

19:29.880 --> 19:32.634
He's not getting off that easy.
Jesus, Hank.

19:32.800 --> 19:35.759
And the same goes for you
if you stick with him.

19:37.520 --> 19:40.354
Both of you think you're just gonna
walk away from this thing?

19:40.800 --> 19:42.393
Never gonna happen.

19:42.560 --> 19:45.951
That is not what we're saying.
Enough with the bullshit.

19:48.880 --> 19:51.714
You're not gonna negotiate
your way out of this thing.

19:51.880 --> 19:55.840
There's only one solution: Step up,
be a man and admit what you've done.

19:56.000 --> 19:58.151
That's it. There is no other option.

20:15.840 --> 20:17.718
Let's go.

20:34.320 --> 20:36.789
<i>My name is Walter Hartwell White.</i>

20:37.000 --> 20:39.640
<i>I live at 308 Negra Arroyo Lane,</i>

20:39.840 --> 20:43.470
<i>Albuquerque, New Mexico, 87104.</i>

20:44.320 --> 20:46.391
<i>This is my confession.</i>

20:46.840 --> 20:48.991
<i>If you're watching this tape,</i>

20:49.600 --> 20:51.353
<i>I'm probably dead,</i>

20:51.920 --> 20:55.357
<i>murdered by my brother-in-law,
Hank Schrader.</i>

20:56.440 --> 20:59.194
<i>Hank has been building
a meth empire</i>

20:59.400 --> 21:03.155
<i>for over a year now
and using me as his chemist.</i>

21:03.360 --> 21:06.034
<i>Shortly after my 50th birthday,</i>

21:06.240 --> 21:08.550
<i>he asked that I use
my chemistry knowledge</i>

21:08.720 --> 21:12.873
<i>to cook methamphetamine,
which he would then sell</i>

21:13.080 --> 21:17.950
<i>using connections that he made
through his career with the DEA.</i>

21:18.720 --> 21:23.158
<i>I was astounded. I...</i>

21:23.320 --> 21:26.757
<i>I always thought Hank
was a very moral man</i>

21:26.920 --> 21:29.958
<i>and I was particularly
vulnerable at the time,</i>

21:30.120 --> 21:31.679
<i>something he knew</i>

21:31.840 --> 21:33.991
<i>and took advantage of.</i>

21:35.120 --> 21:37.760
<i>I was reeling
from a cancer diagnosis</i>

21:37.920 --> 21:41.630
<i>that was poised
to bankrupt my family.</i>

